data.content:
## What Breaks in .NET 11

In .NET 11 / EF Core 11, the **sync-over-async opt-in for the Cosmos DB provider is removed entirely**. The configuration you had (e.g., `CosmosOptionsExtension.EnableSyncOverAsync`) no longer suppresses the exception.

Every synchronous LINQ operator — `ToList()`, `First()`, `Count()`, and `SaveChanges()` — will throw an **`InvalidOperationException`** at runtime because the Cosmos DB provider only supports async I/O.

## The Fix

Convert to async equivalents:

```csharp
public class ProductRepository
{
    private readonly CosmosDbContext _context;

    public async Task<List<Product>> GetAllAsync()
    {
        return await _context.Products.ToListAsync();
    }

    public async Task<Product> GetByIdAsync(int id)
    {
        return await _context.Products.FirstAsync(p => p.Id == id);
    }

    public async Task<int> GetCountAsync()
    {
        return await _context.Products.CountAsync();
    }

    public async Task SaveAsync(Product product)
    {
        _context.Products.Add(product);
        await _context.SaveChangesAsync();
    }
}
```

**Key changes:**
- `ToList()` → `ToListAsync()` + `await`
- `First()` → `FirstAsync()` + `await`
- `Count()` → `CountAsync()` + `await`
- `SaveChanges()` → `SaveChangesAsync()` + `await`
- Return types become `Task<T>` / `Task`
- Methods renamed with `Async` suffix (convention)

Note that `Add()` stays synchronous — it only tracks the entity in memory; no I/O occurs until `SaveChangesAsync()`. The async LINQ methods require `using Microsoft.EntityFrameworkCore`.

This will ripple up through your call chain — callers of these methods must also become `async`/`await`.
